"Mander Ü., Kuusemets V., Lõhmus K., Mauring T., Teiter S., Augustin J.","Nitrous oxide, dinitrogen and methane emission in a subsurface flow constructed wetland",2003,"Water Science and Technology","48","5",,"135","142",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0242637050&partnerID=40&md5=11320510489cfb189f21329a876d4266","Institute of Geography, University of Tartu, 46 Vanemuise St., 51014 Tartu, Estonia; Ctr. for Ecological Eng. Tartu CEET, 4 J.V. Jannseni St., 51005 Tartu, Estonia; Inst. of Prim. Prod./Microbial Ecol., Ctr. Agric. Landscape/Land Use Res., D-15374 Müncheberg, Germany","Mander, Ü., Institute of Geography, University of Tartu, 46 Vanemuise St., 51014 Tartu, Estonia; Kuusemets, V., Institute of Geography, University of Tartu, 46 Vanemuise St., 51014 Tartu, Estonia; Lõhmus, K., Institute of Geography, University of Tartu, 46 Vanemuise St., 51014 Tartu, Estonia; Mauring, T., Ctr. for Ecological Eng. Tartu CEET, 4 J.V. Jannseni St., 51005 Tartu, Estonia; Teiter, S., Institute of Geography, University of Tartu, 46 Vanemuise St., 51014 Tartu, Estonia; Augustin, J., Inst. of Prim. Prod./Microbial Ecol., Ctr. Agric. Landscape/Land Use Res., D-15374 Müncheberg, Germany","N2O, N2 and CH4 fluxes were measured from a horizontal subsurface flow (HSSF) constructed wetland (CW) for wastewater treatment in Estonia. The closed chamber method was used in the field and the He-O method (intact soil core analyses) in the lab throughout the period from October 2001 to June 2002. The average flux of N2O-N, N2-N and CH4-C from various microsites ranged from 0.1 to 59, 4.1 to 1,458 and -0.04 to 2,094 mg m2 d-1, respectively. A significantly higher flux of N2O was found in chambers installed above the inlet pipes, while the methane flux was higher in the inlet part of the bed with wetter conditions. The groundwater table significantly correlates with gas emission rates of all the gases studied; N2 emission was enhanced by higher temperature of wastewater. PO43- and NH4+ content significantly enhanced, and NO2- and NO3- content inhibited, both N2O and CH4 fluxes. NH4+ showed a negative correlation with N2 flux. Nitrification and denitrification are the main processes of the N removal in the CW covering 42.9%. The specific global warming potential was highest in the wet bed and lowest in the dry bed with lowered water table (32 and 9 g CO2 pe-1 d-1, respectively).","Dentrification; Global warming potential; Methane","Denitrification; Gas emissions; Global warming; Methane; Nitrification; Wastewater treatment; Wetlands; Closed chamber method; Nitrogen oxides; ammonia; methane; nitrous oxide; phosphate; calculation; conference paper; constructed wetland; correlation analysis; denitrification; Estonia; flow; gas; greenhouse effect; high temperature; nitrification; sampling; soil analysis; statistical analysis; waste component removal; waste water management; Biodegradation, Environmental; Ecosystem; Environmental Monitoring; Methane; Nitrogen; Nitrous Oxide; Waste Disposal, Fluid; Water Purification",,"ammonia, 14798-03-9, 51847-23-5, 7664-41-7; methane, 74-82-8; nitrous oxide, 10024-97-2; phosphate, 14066-19-4, 14265-44-2; Methane, 74-82-8; Nitrogen, 7727-37-9; Nitrous Oxide, 10024-97-2",,,,"Ambus, P., Christensen, S., Denitrification variability and control in a riparian fen irrigated with agricultural drainage water (1993) Soil Biol. Biochem., 25, pp. 915-923; (1989) Standard Methods for the Examination of Water and Waste Water. 17th Edition, , Washington; Augustin, J., Merbach, W., Schmidt, W., Reining, E., Effect of changing temperature and water table on trace gas emission from minerotrophic mires (1996) J. Appl. Bot., 70, pp. 45-51; Bachand, P.A.M., Horne, A.J., Denitrification in constructed free-water surface wetlands: I. Very high nitrate removal rates in a macrocosm study (2000) Ecol. Eng., 14 (1-2), pp. 9-15; Brix, H., Sorrell, B.K., Lorenzen, B., Are Phragmites-dominated wetlands a net source or net sink of greenh